**Unit 1.4 — Meteorological Parameters**. Here's how to use it to crack JRF:

The "All Parameters" tab gives you a quick reference table — instruments and units are tested directly in MCQs, so memorise them. The "Humidity & Mixing" tab has an interactive calculator: drag the temperature slider and watch how saturation mixing ratio changes — this builds the intuition you need for cloud formation and stability questions. The "Lapse Rates" tab covers the most conceptually heavy topic in this section — the DALR, SALR, ELR comparison and temperature inversion. The "Wind Rose" tab shows a live diagram with the prevailing wind marked. Finally, the "Practice MCQs" tab has 10 exam-pattern questions with detailed explanations.

**Key things to absolutely nail for JRF:**

The relationship between ELR and DALR for atmospheric stability is a perennial favourite. Temperature inversion as a pollution trap (always links to Unit 6 — air pollution dispersion) is asked repeatedly. The difference between mixing ratio and saturation mixing ratio confuses many students — the interactive calculator will fix that. Wind rose interpretation (especially that wind direction is named from where it comes, not where it goes) is a common trick question.

**Study tip:** After going through each tab here, link these concepts forward — lapse rates connect directly to Gaussian plume models (Unit 6.6), humidity connects to precipitation and hydrological cycle (Unit 2.3), and wind roses are used in EIA siting (Unit 8). JRF questions often test these cross-unit connections.

